NODE_1_length_170810_cov_107.538502	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	89854	91686	.	-	0	ID=MGA_77;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;;locus_tag=LOCUS_00770;note=WP_189471990.1 TDP-N-acetylfucosamine:lipid II N-acetylfucosaminyltransferase (Halomonas qijiaojingensis) [pid:22.4%25%2C q_cov:55.6%25%2C s_cov:90.1%25%2C Eval:4.9e-17%2C partial hit],TIGR:TIGR03570%3B NeuD_NnaD: sugar O-acyltransferase%2C sialic acid O-acetyltransferase NeuD family [Name:TIGR03570%2C Eval:9.3e-19%2C score:65.8%2C bias:0.1],Domain:cl28358:LpxD UDP-3-O-[3-hydroxymyristoyl] glucosamine N-acyltransferase [Cell wall/membrane/envelope biogenesis]. This model describes LpxD%2C an enzyme for the biosynthesis of lipid A%2C a component oflipopolysaccharide (LPS) in the outer membrane outer leaflet of most Gram-negative bacteria. Some differences are found between lipid A of different species. This protein represents the third step from UDP-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine. The group added at this step generally is 14:0(3-OH) (myristate) but may vary%3B in Aquifex it appears to be 16:0(3-OH) (palmitate). [Cell envelope%2C Biosynthesis and degradation of surface polysaccharides and lipopolysaccharides] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:511-586%2C Eval:1.0e-10%2C score:60.4%2C C-term missing],MGA_77
NODE_1_length_170810_cov_107.538502	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	91735	92943	.	-	0	ID=MGA_78;product=ATP-grasp domain-containing protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_011108800.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_00780;note=WP_011108800.1 ATP-grasp domain-containing protein (Bacteroides thetaiotaomicron) [pid:33.7%25%2C q_cov:98.3%25%2C s_cov:99.7%25%2C Eval:8.1e-60],Domain:cl27719:Biotin_carb_N Biotin carboxylase%2C N-terminal domain. Carbamoyl-phosphate synthase (CPSase) catalyzes the first committed step in pyrimidine%2C arginine%2C and urea biosynthesis. In general%2C it is a glutamine-dependent enzyme%2C EC 6.3.5.5%2C termed CPSase II in eukaryotes. An exception is the mammalian mitochondrial urea-cycle form%2C CPSase I%2C in which the glutamine amidotransferase domain active site Cys on the small subunit has been lost%2C and the enzyme is ammonia-dependent. In both CPSase I and the closely related%2C glutamine-dependent CPSase III (allosterically activated by acetyl-glutamate) demonstrated in some other vertebrates%2C the small and large chain regions are fused in a single polypeptide chain. This model represents the large chain of glutamine-hydrolysing carbamoyl-phosphate synthases%2C or the corresponding regions of larger%2C multifunctional proteins%2C as found in all domains of life%2C and CPSase I forms are considered exceptions within the family. In several thermophilic species (Methanobacterium thermoautotrophicum%2C Methanococcus jannaschii%2C Aquifex aeolicus)%2C the large subunit appears split%2C at different points%2C into two separate genes. [Purines%2C pyrimidines%2C nucleosides%2C and nucleotides%2C Pyrimidine ribonucleotide biosynthesis] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:5-318%2C Eval:9.8e-18%2C score:81.5%2C C-term missing],MGA_78
