NODE_3_length_150764_cov_89.764227	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	85340	86146	.	+	0	ID=MGA_332;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MDIQWSLVLFTALTGMGGWLFFFICLNVFVRKTDKGAFAGTATALALTVVGGLASVTHLSHPDRMLGALQHPTSGIFTEALLVGLLAIVMIAFLVMLRRGIDGGALKAVAVVGMALGALMSFMAGQSYLMSAIAAWNTELLPLGYLGTAAASGAAAYLVLIAAQKADENACSLYGLMTLAAGCVALITVLAYGAVAGAFAGDAAPMTIAAAAFGGVAPIACGFLARKKPGSAVALGAVALIAALIGSIAFRCAMWVIGAGLYDFFGLI;locus_tag=LOCUS_03320;note=Domain:cl21513:NrfD Polysulphide reductase%2C NrfD. Bacterial polysulfide reductase is an integral membrane protein complex responsible for quinone-coupled reduction of polysulfide%2C a process important in extreme environments such as deep-sea vents and hot springs. Polysulfides are a class of compounds composed of chains of sulfur atoms%2C which in their simplest form are present as an anion with general formula Sn(2-). In nature%2C polysulfides are found in particularly high concentrations in extreme volcanic or geothermically active environments. Here%2C the reduction and oxidation of polysulfides are vital processes for many bacteria and are essential steps in the global sulfur cycle. In particular%2C the reduction of polysulfide to hydrogen sulfide in these environments is usually linked to energy-generating respiratory processes%2C supporting growth of many microorganisms%2C particularly hyperthermophiles. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:5-148%2C Eval:4.0e-07%2C score:46.9%2C C-term missing],MGA_332
