NODE_5_length_133089_cov_81.262315	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	106257	107111	.	+	0	ID=MGA_598;product=dimethyl sulfoxide reductase anchor subunit;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_002209429.1;translation=MTSGFDAFSLGLFTSLAPAGVVAFLALALVRLWSRDRTASVRIDRMIALPFSVVLIGFIASATHLGTPANALHVFSGVGRSPLSNEVLSAVAFLFLVGSYWMMAFKERFPDAVAKPWLALACLAGIALIACTSMAYNVDTVPTWDTAFTPANLVLAALLAGPVLGLLFLELAQVRPRALERALVVLAAPALVAGTVVLALHQESLPAIANNEFAASTLAPSYPAVIGAHLIVGAIALAIAGLSMKRVQSRRTTLALRATASLLALAAVFVTRIVFYHLHMTVGF;locus_tag=LOCUS_05970;note=WP_002209429.1 dimethyl sulfoxide reductase anchor subunit (Yersinia pseudotuberculosis complex) [pid:28.2%25%2C q_cov:99.6%25%2C s_cov:98.3%25%2C Eval:1.3e-28],Domain:cl21513:NrfD Polysulphide reductase%2C NrfD. Bacterial polysulfide reductase is an integral membrane protein complex responsible for quinone-coupled reduction of polysulfide%2C a process important in extreme environments such as deep-sea vents and hot springs. Polysulfides are a class of compounds composed of chains of sulfur atoms%2C which in their simplest form are present as an anion with general formula Sn(2-). In nature%2C polysulfides are found in particularly high concentrations in extreme volcanic or geothermically active environments. Here%2C the reduction and oxidation of polysulfides are vital processes for many bacteria and are essential steps in the global sulfur cycle. In particular%2C the reduction of polysulfide to hydrogen sulfide in these environments is usually linked to energy-generating respiratory processes%2C supporting growth of many microorganisms%2C particularly hyperthermophiles. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:7-283%2C Eval:8.7e-31%2C score:113.6],MGA_598
