NODE_12_length_99619_cov_64.031183	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	79568	80935	.	-	0	ID=MGA_1306;product=putative manganese-dependent inorganic diphosphatase;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_011393891.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_12990;EC_number=3.6.1.1;note=WP_011393891.1 putative manganese-dependent inorganic diphosphatase (Moorella thermoacetica) [pid:35.8%25%2C q_cov:98.5%25%2C s_cov:97.7%25%2C Eval:1.1e-71],COG:COG1227:PPX1 Inorganic pyrophosphatase/exopolyphosphatase [Category:CP%2C Aligned:187-448%2C Eval:1.5e-67%2C score:215.7],Domain:cl15354:CBS_pair N/A. CBS domains are small intracellular modules that pair together to form a stable globular domain. This family represents a single CBS domain. Pairs of these domains have been termed a Bateman domain. CBS domains have been shown to bind ligands with an adenosyl group such as AMP%2C ATP and S-AdoMet. CBS domains are found attached to a wide range of other protein domains suggesting that CBS domains may play a regulatory role making proteins sensitive to adenosyl carrying ligands. The region containing the CBS domains in Cystathionine-beta synthase is involved in regulation by S-AdoMet. CBS domain pairs from AMPK bind AMP or ATP. The CBS domains from IMPDH and the chloride channel CLC2 bind ATP. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:79-212%2C Eval:9.2e-13%2C score:65.8%2C N-term missing],MGA_1306
NODE_12_length_99619_cov_64.031183	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	81226	82836	.	+	0	ID=MGA_1307;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;;locus_tag=LOCUS_13000;note=WP_011460513.1 L-serine ammonia-lyase%2C iron-sulfur-dependent%2C subunit alpha (Desulfitobacterium hafniense) [pid:50.4%25%2C q_cov:43.7%25%2C s_cov:81.5%25%2C Eval:1.7e-58%2C partial hit],TIGR:TIGR00718%3B sda_alpha: L-serine dehydratase%2C iron-sulfur-dependent%2C alpha subunit [Name:TIGR00718%2C Eval:3.5e-77%2C score:257.4%2C bias:15.1],COG:COG1760:SdaA L-serine deaminase [Category:E%2C Aligned:261-524%2C Eval:1.1e-54%2C score:182.4],Domain:cl27283:SdaA L-serine deaminase [Amino acid transport and metabolism]. This enzyme is also called serine deaminase and L-serine dehydratase 1. L-serine ammonia-lyase converts serine into pyruvate in the gluconeogenesis pathway from serine. This enzyme is comprised of a single chain in Escherichia coli%2C Mycobacterium tuberculosis%2C and several other species%2C but has separate alpha and beta chains in Bacillus subtilis and related species. The beta and alpha chains are homologous to the N-terminal and C-terminal regions%2C respectively%2C but are rather deeply branched in a UPGMA tree. This enzyme requires iron and dithiothreitol for activation in vitro%2C and is a predicted 4Fe-4S protein. Escherichia coli Pseudomonas aeruginosa have two copies of this protein. [Energy metabolism%2C Amino acids and amines%2C Energy metabolism%2C Glycolysis/gluconeogenesis] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:8-221%2C Eval:4.4e-30%2C score:115.8],MGA_1307
