NODE_15_length_87708_cov_86.146044	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	35839	36417	.	-	0	ID=MGA_1544;product=acyltransferase;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_012582951.1;translation=MTAPYVHESSYADEGVAIGDDTKVWHFCHIQSGASIGRGCSLGQNVYVGANAKIGDGVKIQNNVSVYEGVELGDHVFCGPSCVFTNDLTPRAKYPKGGDGYKRTVVRRGASIGANATIVCGHEIGAWAMVGSGAVVTSDVPPHALVLGVPARQRGWACECGAVLSEDLACSACGRTYAQSDEGLKEVQHGVS;locus_tag=LOCUS_15330;note=WP_012582951.1 acyltransferase (Dictyoglomus turgidum) [pid:63.5%25%2C q_cov:92.2%25%2C s_cov:92.8%25%2C Eval:1.6e-62],Domain:cl28262:PaaY Carbonic anhydrase or acetyltransferase%2C isoleucine patch superfamily [General function prediction only]. This family of proteins includes the characterized NeuD sialic acid O-acetyltransferase enzymes from E. coli and Streptococcus agalactiae (group B strep). These two are quite closely related to one another%2C so extension of this annotation to other members of the family in unsupported without additional independent evidence. The neuD gene is often observed in close proximity to the neuABC genes for the biosynthesis of CMP-N-acetylneuraminic acid (CMP-sialic acid)%2C and NeuD sequences from these organisms were used to construct the seed for this model. Nevertheless%2C there are numerous instances of sequences identified by this model which are observed in a different genomic context (although almost universally in exopolysaccharide biosynthesis-related loci)%2C as well as in genomes for which the biosynthesis of sialic acid (SA) is undemonstrated. Even in the cases where the association with SA biosynthesis is strong%2C it is unclear in the literature whether the biological substrate is SA iteself%2C CMP-SA%2C or a polymer containing SA. Similarly%2C it is unclear to what extent the enzyme has a preference for acetylation at the 7%2C 8 or 9 positions. In the absence of evidence of association with SA%2C members of this family may be involved with the acetylation of differring sugar substrates%2C or possibly the delivery of alternative acyl groups. The closest related sequences to this family (and those used to root the phylogenetic tree constructed to create this model) are believed to be succinyltransferases involved in lysine biosynthesis. These proteins contain repeats of the bacterial transferase hexapeptide (pfam00132)%2C although often these do not register above the trusted cutoff. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:22-152%2C Eval:4.3e-20%2C score:80.4%2C N-term missing],MGA_1544
