NODE_20_length_68963_cov_57.970618	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	21702	22013	.	+	0	ID=MGA_1884;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MAATATLNVRLPEDLKDRGAQVLRREGVSVSDAVRGLYEYMEKEQRLPEFIKPANEDARRSAVERKRSTLRDMAGVLSPSPCTEARDEWREHLEWKTRPGVRT;locus_tag=LOCUS_18720;note=TIGR:TIGR02384%3B RelB_DinJ: addiction module antitoxin%2C RelB/DinJ family [Name:TIGR02384%2C Eval:4.3e-09%2C score:34.5%2C bias:0.0],Domain:cl01171:RelB RelB antitoxin. Plasmids may be maintained stably in bacterial populations through the action of addiction modules%2C in which a toxin and antidote are encoded in a cassette on the plasmid. In any daughter cell that lacks the plasmid%2C the toxin persists and is lethal after the antidote protein is depleted. Toxin/antitoxin pairs are also found on main chromosomes%2C and likely represent selfish DNA. Sequences in the seed for this alignment all were found adjacent to toxin genes. The resulting model appears to describe a narrower set of proteins than pfam04221%2C although many in the scope of this model are not obviously paired with toxin proteins. Several toxin/antitoxin pairs may occur in a single species. [Cellular processes%2C Toxin production and resistance%2C Mobile and extrachromosomal element functions%2C Other] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:1-57%2C Eval:3.7e-10%2C score:49.3%2C C-term missing],MGA_1884
