NODE_53_length_14461_cov_58.072789	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	6500	7309	.	-	0	ID=MGA_2863;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MVFWIALVVFVVALAALGAIGFSYWQGQQTYNDVAREGFTPPDDLSATSLADFTVDWDALKAINPDTVGWIYIPGTVVNYPIVQAADDEKYLTHDFKGSEGWIATFGAIFLAAENSSDFSDPNNIIYGHHLNDGSMFACVADFSDAAQFNDHRTVYILTPEGNYELSTFALVHVAADDPLAQMRFADEDERVAYVQDKIDRSVVPASDIPAASDIKHTFALATCDNLPSDGRYVLYSYVKASTVGEGDGDVIDPDAVAAIDSAEQEIAS;locus_tag=LOCUS_28370;note=WP_000095595.1 class B sortase (Bacillus) [pid:32.6%25%2C q_cov:66.5%25%2C s_cov:69.3%25%2C Eval:1.2e-20%2C partial hit],TIGR:TIGR03064%3B sortase_srtB: sortase%2C SrtB family [Name:TIGR03064%2C Eval:2.0e-47%2C score:159.5%2C bias:0.0],Domain:cl09098:Sortase Sortase domain. Class D sortases are cysteine transpeptidases distributed in Gram-positive bacteria (mainly present in Firmicutes). They anchor surface proteins bearing a cell wall sorting signal to peptidoglycans of the bacterial cell wall envelope%2C which is responsible for spore formation under anaerobic conditions. This involves a transpeptidation reaction in which the surface protein substrate is cleaved at the cell wall sorting signal and covalently linked to peptidoglycan for display on the bacterial surface. The prototypical subfamily 2 of class D sortase from Clostridium perfringens (named Cp-SrtD) recognizes the LPQTGS signal motif for transpeptidation. Its catalytic activity is in a metal cation- and temperature- dependent manner. The presence of magnesium appears to enhance Cp-SrtD catalysis towards the LPQTGS signal motif. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:5-235%2C Eval:5.9e-38%2C score:131.1],MGA_2863
NODE_53_length_14461_cov_58.072789	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	7914	9650	.	-	0	ID=MGA_2864;product=polyphosphate:AMP phosphotransferase;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_012869086.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_28380;gene=pap;note=WP_012869086.1 polyphosphate:AMP phosphotransferase (Thermanaerovibrio acidaminovorans) [pid:37.2%25%2C q_cov:99.5%25%2C s_cov:99.6%25%2C Eval:3.2e-103],Domain:cl11971:PPK2 Polyphosphate kinase 2 (PPK2). Members of this protein family belong to the polyphosphate kinase 2 (PPK2) family%2C which is not related in sequence to PPK1. While PPK1 tends to act in the biosynthesis of polyphosphate%2C or poly(P)%2C members of the PPK2 family tend to use the terminal phosphate of poly(P) to regenerate ATP or GTP from the corresponding nucleoside diphosphate%2C or ADP from AMP as is the case with polyphosphate:AMP phosphotransferase (PAP). Members of this protein family most likely transfer the terminal phosphate between poly(P) and some nucleotide%2C but it is not clear which. [Central intermediary metabolism%2C Phosphorus compounds] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:343-577%2C Eval:3.0e-94%2C score:286.9],Domain:cl11971:PPK2 Polyphosphate kinase 2 (PPK2). Members of this protein family belong to the polyphosphate kinase 2 (PPK2) family%2C which is not related in sequence to PPK1. While PPK1 tends to act in the biosynthesis of polyphosphate%2C or poly(P)%2C members of the PPK2 family tend to use the terminal phosphate of poly(P) to regenerate ATP or GTP from the corresponding nucleoside diphosphate%2C or ADP from AMP as is the case with polyphosphate:AMP phosphotransferase (PAP). Members of this protein family most likely transfer the terminal phosphate between poly(P) and some nucleotide%2C but it is not clear which. [Central intermediary metabolism%2C Phosphorus compounds] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:12-270%2C Eval:9.7e-31%2C score:118.2],MGA_2864
